"""
MKT Context Commentary — Genesis chapters 7–9
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-genesis-7-9.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/genesis.json
- data/translation/draft/mediating/genesis.json (MKT text)
- data/commentary/mkt-context/genesis.json (merge_comm skips any existing entries)

Key decisions in this range:
- Ch 7:11: "springs of the great deep / floodgates of heaven" treated as ANE cosmological
  reversal of Day 2 (separation of waters), not merely heavy rain
- Ch 8:1: "God remembered Noah" treated as covenantal action-vocabulary, not mere recall
- Ch 8:4: Ararat/Urartu identified geographically; 17th-of-7th-month typological note included
- Ch 8:21: Post-flood repetition of "every inclination evil" noted as confirming flood did not
  solve human sin; Noahic covenant is unconditional
- Ch 9:6: Image of God explicitly the theological ground for blood-prohibition/capital punishment
- Ch 9:22-25: Ham's offense treated with the ANE honor-shame framework; the
  grotesque misuse of the "curse of Ham" for racial slavery noted and refuted
- Ch 9:13: qeshet (bow/rainbow) treated as possible ANE warrior-bow-laying-down background
- Ch 9:16: bĕrit ʿôlam (everlasting covenant) identified as first in a chain of canonical
  everlasting covenants
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

GENESIS_CONTEXT = {
  "7": {
    "1": """<p>YHWH's declaration "I have found you righteous (<em>ṣaddîq</em>) in this generation" activates the covenant relationship that was only hinted at in 6:8-9. The Hebrew <em>ṣaddîq</em> carries the forensic sense of right standing before a judge — Noah is vindicated rather than merely morally praised. This declaration stands in striking contrast to the Mesopotamian flood traditions: in the Atra-hasis and Gilgamesh epics, the flood-hero (Utnapishtim) was chosen by one god (Ea/Enki) against the will of the other gods, without explicit moral reasoning. Genesis establishes the flood's theological rationale as moral from the outset: Noah is preserved because of who he is before YHWH, not because of a deity's favoritism in a divine council dispute.</p>""",
    "2": """<p>The clean/unclean animal distinction (seven pairs of clean, one pair of unclean) predates the Mosaic law by centuries, demonstrating that the ritual categories of clean and unclean were not Levitical innovations but pre-existing categories with primordial roots (cf. Lev 11; Deut 14). The practical purpose of the extra clean animals is revealed in 8:20: Noah takes "some of all the clean animals" for burnt offerings immediately upon exiting the ark. The sevenfold provision of clean animals anticipates the sacrificial needs before any law commands them — the covenant relationship implies worship before the law specifies it.</p>""",
    "3": """<p>The extension of the clean/unclean distinction to birds (seven pairs of clean birds) anticipates Lev 11:13-19's classification of clean and unclean birds. The care given to preserving bird species beyond the minimum one pair for unclean types reflects both the provision for future sacrifice (clean birds were used in Lev 1:14-17; 14:4-7) and the concern for the full restoration of the created ecosystem. The phrase "to keep their various kinds (<em>miyyôt</em>) alive throughout the earth" echoes the creation of creatures "according to their kinds" in Gen 1:21,24-25; the preservation restores the creation taxonomy.</p>""",
    "4": """<p>The "forty days and forty nights" rain period inaugurates one of the Bible's most pervasive symbolic numbers. Forty as a period of judgment, transition, or formation recurs with remarkable consistency: Moses on Sinai (Exod 24:18; 34:28), Israel's wilderness wandering (Num 14:33-34), Elijah's journey to Horeb (1 Kgs 19:8), Jonah's warning to Nineveh (Jon 3:4), and Jesus's wilderness temptation (Matt 4:2; Mark 1:13; Luke 4:2). Whether the number is conventional/symbolic in the ANE context (Mesopotamian texts also use 40-day periods for significant transitions) or precisely literal, the pattern links the flood to subsequent acts of divine judgment and covenant renewal.</p>""",
    "5": """<p>The second appearance of the comprehensive obedience formula "Noah did all that the LORD commanded him" (cf. 6:22) is not redundant but structurally deliberate. The narrative requires the reader to understand that Noah's faithful obedience — and not merely divine favoritism — is the qualifying characteristic of the covenant-servant. The flood narrative is framed between two obedience statements (6:22 and 7:5) as bookends, just as the tabernacle-building narrative will be framed by the same formula (Exod 39:43; 40:16). Complete covenant obedience is the biblical mark of the servant through whom YHWH preserves and re-creates.</p>""",
    "6": """<p>The precise notation of Noah's age at the flood (600 years) locates the event within the chronological system of the antediluvian genealogy (ch5). The internal chronology of Genesis, calculated by adding the lifespans and birth-ages of the ch5 patriarchs, places the flood 1,656 years after creation. This specificity is without parallel in ANE flood traditions: the Gilgamesh and Atra-hasis epics place their flood heroes in a vague primordial age without a calculable timeline. Genesis treats the flood as a dateable event within a continuous chronological record from creation to the patriarchs — a historiographical claim, not merely a mythological archetype.</p>""",
    "7": """<p>The ark's passengers are listed as a covenant household unit: Noah, sons, wife, sons' wives — the same eight-person unit as in the covenant-invitation of 6:18. The ANE understanding of covenant was fundamentally household-based: the patriarch's covenant-status extended to all members of his household (cf. Gen 17:12-13 where the household inclusion in the Abrahamic covenant is spelled out explicitly). The ark functions as a covenant-household vessel: the community inside is defined by its relationship to the covenant mediator (Noah), not by individual merit.</p>""",
    "8": """<p>The fourfold classification of creatures entering the ark — clean animals, unclean animals, birds, all ground creatures — mirrors the creation taxonomy of days 5-6 (Gen 1:20-25). The flood narrative is systematically structured to parallel the creation narrative: every category that was created and declared "good" is now being preserved against the un-creation event of the flood. The phrase "pairs of clean and unclean animals" without yet specifying numbers rehearses the categories before the specific account of entry (vv15-16). The doubling of the entry narrative (vv7-9 and vv13-16) follows biblical prose convention of general statement followed by specific elaboration.</p>""",
    "9": """<p>"Male and female came to Noah and entered the ark, as God had commanded Noah" — the divine orchestration of the animal-gathering echoes 2:19, where God "brought [the animals] to Adam." The same divine initiative that brought creatures to the first human for naming now brings them to Noah for preservation. The passive construal of the animals' arrival ("came to Noah") with the divine command as its explanation reflects the narrative's insistence that the flood preservation is entirely God's doing, with Noah as the obedient instrument. No account is given of Noah herding or capturing animals — they come, because God commanded it.</p>""",
    "10": """<p>The seven-day waiting period between completing ark-loading and the flood's arrival (cf. 7:4: "seven days from now I will send rain") echoes the seven-day structure of creation. The week-long preparatory pause before the judgment mirrors the week-long creation of the world — both creation and its reversal are bounded by a seven-day structure. The Atra-hasis epic (one of the primary Mesopotamian flood parallels) similarly specifies a seven-day preparatory period before the flood begins. The shared seven-day pattern may reflect a common ancient convention for marking epochs of decisive divine action.</p>""",
    "11": """<p>The dual cosmological mechanism — "all the springs of the great deep (<em>tĕhôm raḇ</em>) burst forth, and the floodgates (<em>ʾărubbôt</em>) of the heavens were opened" — is the narrative's most cosmologically significant detail. ANE cosmology understood the world as surrounded by waters held back by the created order: below the earth, the <em>tĕhôm</em> (primordial deep); above the firmament (<em>rāqîaʿ</em>), the upper waters restrained by the dome. The creation of Day 2 (Gen 1:6-8) separated these waters; the flood is the reversal of that separation. The springs of the deep and the windows of the firmament both open simultaneously: this is not merely heavy rain but the collapse of the created order's water-boundaries — a cosmic un-creation event. The precise date (sixth-hundredth year, second month, seventeenth day) frames this cosmological event as chronologically anchored history.</p>""",
    "12": """<p>The forty-day rain period (see v4) is the first phase of the flood's intensification. The Gilgamesh epic specifies "six days and seven nights" of storm; the Atra-hasis epic has seven days. Genesis's forty days is distinctive and connected to its broader symbolic-chronological system. The flood narrative then specifies separate phases: forty days of rain, 150 days of peak flooding (7:24), then a gradual recession over seven months. This staged chronology is more meteorologically elaborated than any ANE parallel and gives the Genesis account a character closer to historical record than to mythological archetype.</p>""",
    "13": """<p>The "on that very day" reiteration of the entry narrative (with the full list of names: Noah, Shem, Ham, Japheth, wife, sons' wives) is a literary device characteristic of biblical prose: a general account (vv7-9) followed by a date-stamped formal repetition for emphasis and record. The specific naming of the three sons here — Shem, Ham, Japheth — in the flood entry anticipates their significance in the post-flood narrative (ch9:18-27; ch10 Table of Nations). Their presence in the ark as named individuals, not merely as "Noah's sons," begins to establish their individual covenant trajectories.</p>""",
    "14": """<p>The four-fold classification of preserved creatures — wild animals (<em>ḥayyāh</em>), livestock (<em>bĕhēmāh</em>), ground-moving creatures (<em>remeś</em>), and birds (<em>ʿôp</em>) — exactly mirrors the creation taxonomy of Gen 1:20-25. The structural parallelism is deliberate: what God created and declared good (1:25,31), God now preserves in the ark. The phrase "everything with wings" (kōl-ṣipôr kol-kānāp) adds a comprehensive catch-all that ensures no creature type is overlooked. The ark's cargo is the creation's living library — every kind preserved against the un-creation event of the flood.</p>""",
    "15": """<p>"Pairs of all creatures that have the breath of life (<em>nišmat-rûaḥ ḥayyîm</em>) in them came to Noah" — the compound phrase "breath/spirit of life" echoes 2:7 (YHWH breathing <em>nišmat ḥayyîm</em> into Adam) and anticipates 7:22 (everything with "breath of life in its nostrils" dying in the flood). The principle of the ark's preservation is the breath-of-life criterion: what lives by divine breath is preserved within the ark. Outside, the same breath will be extinguished. The ark is the bounded space within which divine life-giving continues while judgment withdraws life-breath from everything outside.</p>""",
    "16": """<p>"Then the LORD shut him in" (<em>wayyisgōr YHWH baʿădô</em>) — YHWH himself closes and seals the ark door. This is one of the narrative's most theologically significant details: it is not Noah who seals himself in but YHWH who seals him in from outside. The one inside is protected by the same hand that executes the judgment outside. The closed door is both the boundary of covenant-preservation and the instrument of the covenant-keeper's own seal. The later image of the shut door in eschatological contexts (Matt 25:10: the door shut on those outside the wedding banquet) echoes this primal sealing.</p>""",
    "17": """<p>As the waters rise over forty days, the ark is "lifted high above the earth" — the Hebrew verb <em>nāśāʾ</em> (to lift, carry, bear) carries the full weight of its semantic range: the ark is not merely floating but being borne upward. The same verb describes the lifting of the serpent in the wilderness (Num 21:8-9; John 3:14). The spatial dynamic of the flood narrative is theological: the ark rises while everything else perishes — elevation above the destructive waters is the spatial metaphor for covenant-preservation within divine judgment. What is below the waters is under judgment; what is above is held by covenant grace.</p>""",
    "18": """<p>The three-step intensification of the rising waters — "rose and increased greatly" (v18), "rose greatly" (v19), "covered the mountains" (v19) — is deliberate rhetorical escalation. The stepped intensifiers mirror the creation narrative's progressive building ("and God saw that it was good"; each day more complete than the last) but in reverse: the flood's un-creation builds systematically through these rhetorical stages. The narrative's artful parallelism between creation and flood confirms that the author shaped both accounts as theological counterparts — flood as un-creation, covenant as re-creation.</p>""",
    "19": """<p>"All the high mountains under the entire heavens were covered" — the comprehensiveness formula signals the totality of the flood's scope. The phrase "under the entire heavens" (<em>taḥat kol-haššāmayim</em>) is the broadest possible scope formula in Hebrew — equivalent to "everywhere." The ANE reader would understand this as complete: no elevated refuge exists. The Gilgamesh epic similarly describes the flood as covering the mountains; the language of comprehensive coverage is conventional in flood narratives. Whether Genesis intends a global or regional flood (a debate that has occupied interpreters from Origen to the present) is not resolved by the Hebrew vocabulary alone, which uses its maximal comprehensiveness formula regardless of actual geographic scope.</p>""",
    "20": """<p>"The waters rose and covered the mountains to a depth of more than fifteen cubits" (approximately 22 feet / 6.7 meters above the peaks). This depth detail — absent from all ANE parallels — serves a practical narrative function: it confirms that the ark, with its 30-cubit draft (cf. 6:15), could float freely over the submerged mountains without grounding. The precision of the detail (fifteen cubits = half the ark's depth) is consistent with the flood narrative's broader interest in technical specificity. No other ancient flood account includes this kind of navigation-relevant measurement.</p>""",
    "21": """<p>The universal death formula systematically reverses the creation taxonomy of days 5-6. The fourfold list of what died — birds, livestock, wild animals, ground-moving creatures, and all mankind — is the exact inversion of the fourfold preservation list (7:14). Every creature that was created and named and declared good (Gen 1:20-31) is now included in the death-toll. The narrative does not spare the reader the scope of the loss. The theological point is structural: what was comprehensively created is comprehensively un-created, so that what is comprehensively preserved in the ark can be comprehensively re-created after the flood.</p>""",
    "22": """<p>"Everything on dry land that had the breath of life (<em>nišmat rûaḥ ḥayyîm</em>) in its nostrils died" — the withdrawal of the breath-of-life is the exact reversal of 2:7 (YHWH breathing life into Adam). The phrase is carefully constructed: "breath of life in its nostrils" is the creation-definition of living creatures (cf. 7:15); the flood's death is the cessation of that breath in all creatures outside the ark. The ark is the space where the breath continues; outside is the space where it stops. The life/death boundary is the ark's hull.</p>""",
    "23": """<p>"Only Noah was left (<em>wayyiššāʾer raq-Nōaḥ</em>), and those with him in the ark" — this is the first use of the remnant-vocabulary in the Bible. The Hebrew <em>šāʾar</em> (to remain, be left, survive) is the technical term for the theological concept of the remnant: after comprehensive judgment, a preserved remainder. The remnant concept will become foundational to prophetic theology: Isaiah's "<em>šĕʾār yāšûḇ</em>" (a remnant shall return, Isa 7:3; 10:20-22), Amos's remnant of Israel (Amos 5:15), Paul's "remnant chosen by grace" (Rom 11:5). Noah is the first remnant figure — the pattern of total judgment with a preserved covenant-remainder is established here and runs to the end of the canon.</p>""",
    "24": """<p>"The waters flooded the earth for a hundred and fifty days" — the peak-flood duration. The Gilgamesh epic has a much shorter peak flood (approximately fourteen days); the Atra-hasis epic's duration is unclear. Genesis's 150-day figure, combined with the precise chronological stages that follow in ch8, gives the flood narrative a temporal specificity unparalleled in ANE parallels. The 150-day peak ends when God "remembers Noah" (8:1) — the theological turn of the narrative is marked by a date, not merely a divine decision. Covenant faithfulness operates within real time.</p>"""
  },
  "8": {
    "1": """<p>"But God remembered (<em>wayyizkōr</em>) Noah" — the covenant-action verb that pivots the flood narrative from judgment to restoration. Divine remembering in the OT is consistently the theological trigger for covenantal intervention: "God remembered Rachel and opened her womb" (30:22), "God heard their groaning and remembered his covenant with Abraham" (Exod 2:24), "God remembered his holy covenant" (Ps 105:42). To remember is not to recover from forgetfulness but to act in covenant faithfulness — the divine memory is always active; the "remembering" language marks the moment of covenant-action. The wind (<em>rûaḥ</em>) sent over the earth deliberately echoes Gen 1:2 (<em>rûaḥ ʾĕlōhîm</em> hovering over the waters at creation). The same divine wind that ordered the primordial waters now re-orders the flood waters; the recession begins as a new-creation event.</p>""",
    "2": """<p>"The springs of the deep and the floodgates of the heavens had been closed" — the exact reversal of 7:11. The cosmological mechanism of the flood (Day 2's water-separation reversed) is now re-established: the springs seal, the windows close, the rain stops. The narrative's cosmological symmetry is precise: what was opened in 7:11 is closed in 8:2; what was broken in the flood is re-established in the recession. The structural parallelism between flood and creation is complete at the cosmological level: the ordered separation of Day 2 (Gen 1:6-8) was broken; now it is restored. The Noahic covenant (9:8-17) will formalize the commitment never to break it again.</p>""",
    "3": """<p>The waters recede "<em>hālôk wāšôḇ</em>" (going and returning, steadily) — a Hebrew idiom for a gradual, wave-like process. The same idiom is used for the raven's flight in 8:7 and for the gradual progression of events in various wisdom texts. The 150-day reference (connecting back to 7:24) confirms that the peak flood ended at 150 days and the recession now begins. The gradual recession over seven months (from the seventeenth day of the seventh month to the twenty-seventh day of the second month of the following year) contrasts with the rapid forty-day onset. Judgment comes like a burst; restoration comes gradually — a pattern that recurs in the prophetic literature.</p>""",
    "4": """<p>The ark rests on the "mountains of Ararat" (<em>hārē ʾărāraṭ</em>) — the Ararat range (Akkadian Urartu), the highland region of eastern modern Turkey and Armenia between Lake Van and the Caspian Sea. Ararat appears in later biblical texts as the homeland to which Sennacherib's sons fled after assassinating their father (2 Kgs 19:37; Isa 37:38) — it is real, identifiable geography, not mythological landscape. The Gilgamesh epic's flood-boat rests on "Mount Nimush" (also in the Armenian highland region), indicating a shared geographical tradition of flood-ending in the Armenian mountains. The seventeenth day of the seventh month is the same date as the later Feast of Firstfruits in the Mosaic calendar — a coincidence noted by Jewish interpreters as typologically resonant: the ark "rising up" on the day that will celebrate firstfruits from the earth.</p>""",
    "5": """<p>The flood's recession is marked by four visible milestones with precise dates: (1) ark grounds on Ararat (7th month, 17th day); (2) mountaintops become visible (10th month, 1st day — v5); (3) Noah opens the window and sends birds (after 40 more days — v6); (4) ground completely dry (2nd month, 27th day of year 601 — v14). This level of chronological precision — six specific dates across the flood year — has no parallel in any ANE flood narrative. The Gilgamesh and Atra-hasis epics give broad timeframes; Genesis gives a datable record. The precision serves the narrative's implicit claim that these events belong to recoverable chronological history.</p>""",
    "6": """<p>Noah opens the window (<em>ḥallôn</em>) he had made in the ark — the same word used in 7:11 for the "floodgates of heaven" (ʾărubbôt haššāmayim) though not the same word. The arkwindow is the <em>ḥallôn</em>, a standard window opening; the heavenly windows (<em>ʾărubbôt</em>) are the cosmological openings. Noah's opening of the window after forty days is his first active investigation of the changed conditions — he had waited in covenant-obedience, not looking out until the time prescribed. The forty days after the mountaintops appeared (v5) before Noah acts mirrors the flood's own forty-day onset — another structural echo of the narrative's systematic forty-day counting.</p>""",
    "7": """<p>The raven (<em>ʿōrēḇ</em>) flies "back and forth" (<em>yāṣōʾ wāšôḇ</em>) without returning to the ark. Ravens are carrion-eaters and opportunistic scavengers; they can land on floating debris, carcasses, or any available surface — they do not require dry, clean land to perch. The raven's non-return to the ark is therefore an ambiguous signal: it does not establish that dry land exists, only that the raven found enough to subsist on. This first, inconclusive test prepares for the more informative dove-test that follows. The Gilgamesh epic similarly sends out a series of birds (swallow, dove, raven) as reconnaissance, in the same order from least useful to most.</p>""",
    "8": """<p>The dove is sent as a more informative test because doves (<em>yônāh</em>) require clean, dry ground to land on — they cannot rest on water or floating debris. The dove is the precision instrument of the reconnaissance: its behavior will give a clear signal about ground conditions. The dove also carries significant later resonance: the dove that descends on Jesus at his baptism (Matt 3:16; Mark 1:10; Luke 3:22; John 1:32) echoes the dove that signals the end of the flood-judgment and the beginning of new creation. Both doves mark the transition from judgment/water to new-creation conditions.</p>""",
    "9": """<p>"The dove could find nowhere to perch (<em>mānôaḥ lĕrap-raglāh</em>, a resting place for the sole of her foot)" — the word <em>mānôaḥ</em> (resting place) shares its root with Noah's name (<em>nōaḥ</em>, from <em>nûaḥ</em>, to rest). The dove cannot find the <em>mānôaḥ</em> that Noah's own name represents — rest. Noah has not yet arrived at his own namesakecondition; the covenant promise of his name (5:29: "he will comfort us") is not yet realized. Noah's reaching out his hand to take the dove back echoes the pastoral intimacy of the ark-community: the covenant-household cares for the creatures entrusted to it, as Adam cared for the garden.</p>""",
    "10": """<p>The seven-day interval between dove-sendings maintains the narrative's seven-day structural rhythm (cf. the seven-day pre-flood wait, 7:4,10; Lev 12:2; Num 19:11-12 for other seven-day purification/waiting periods). The dove's three sendings (first returning with nothing, v9; second returning with olive leaf, v11; third not returning, v12) form a triple-test pattern common in ANE wisdom literature — each test provides more information than the last, building to the definitive confirmation.</p>""",
    "11": """<p>The freshly plucked olive leaf (<em>ʿălēh-zayit ṭārāp</em>) in the dove's beak carries several layers of meaning. Olive trees grow on hillsides and require a Mediterranean climate — their survival indicates the flood has receded from lower elevations. The word <em>ṭārāp</em> (freshly plucked, living) confirms the leaf is from a living, not dead, tree — vegetation has survived the flood. The olive branch as a symbol of peace, hope, and covenant-restoration derives directly from this narrative — the oldest known use of the olive-as-peace symbol in world literature. Later, the olive oil will become the anointing medium for kings and priests, and the olive tree will be a metaphor for Israel's covenant status (Rom 11:17-24).</p>""",
    "12": """<p>The dove's final departure without returning is the conclusive signal. The triple-test pattern (inconclusive raven; first dove returns; second dove brings leaf; third dove does not return) builds to this definitive resolution. The narrative's restraint is notable: Noah does not exit until God commands him (vv15-16), even though the dove's non-return establishes that dry land is accessible. Faithful waiting for divine authorization rather than acting on one's own initiative is the consistent mark of Noah's character throughout the flood narrative — the same quality that characterized his pre-flood obedience.</p>""",
    "13": """<p>Noah "removed the covering (<em>miksēh</em>) of the ark" — the same word used for the ark's roof-covering in 6:16. The investigation begins with Noah's own observation, but it does not conclude with his own decision. He sees, reports (by implication), and waits. The date (first day of the first month of year 601) gives the visual inspection a festival-calendar resonance: in the later Mosaic calendar, the first day of the first month is the date for setting up the tabernacle (Exod 40:17), the beginning of the covenant-worship year. The dry-ground observation on the new year's day anticipates the tabernacle-setting-up pattern.</p>""",
    "14": """<p>The total flood year: from the second month, seventeenth day of year 600 (7:11) to the second month, twenty-seventh day of year 601 (8:14) = one solar year and ten days. This precise duration (one year and ten days) has no parallel in any ANE flood tradition. The Gilgamesh epic's flood is approximately two weeks long (six days of storm, then several weeks of recession); the Genesis account is over a year. The difference in scale reflects different theological purposes: Genesis's year-long flood is an un-creation/re-creation event of cosmic proportions; the Mesopotamian versions are regional catastrophes.</p>""",
    "15": """<p>God's exit command mirrors the entry command structurally (cf. 7:1: "go into the ark"). God commanded the entry; God commands the exit. Noah's obedient waiting between the dove's final departure (v12) and the divine exit command (v16) is days or weeks of patient waiting without presuming to act on his own observation. This structured obedience — doing nothing without divine authorization even when the conditions clearly permit it — is the behavioral pattern that the narrative holds up as the covenant-servant's defining characteristic.</p>""",
    "16": """<p>"Come out of the ark, you and your wife and your sons and their wives" — the same household list as the entry (7:7). The covenant community exits in the same order it entered: Noah, family, creatures. The structural symmetry of entry and exit frames the flood narrative as a complete covenant-unit — the household that entered under divine protection exits under the same protection. The exit is a birth metaphor: the ark-womb releases its contents into a new creation world. The same household that symbolized pre-flood righteous remnant now becomes the seed of post-flood new humanity.</p>""",
    "17": """<p>"Bring out every kind of living creature... so they can multiply on the earth and be fruitful and increase in number on it" — the fruitfulness and multiplication mandate of 1:22 (birds and sea creatures) and 1:28 (humanity) is here restated for the post-flood creatures as their re-creation mandate. The ark's exit is structured as a new creation: God commands fruitfulness and multiplication as the first post-flood activity, exactly as he did at creation. The flood narrative is consciously shaped as a de-creation/re-creation sequence, with this verse as the re-creation commissioning.</p>""",
    "18": """<p>The orderly exit of Noah's household (Noah, sons, wife, sons' wives) followed by the animals mirrors the orderly entry. The narrative's symmetry is not accidental: the same four-member family listing, in the same order, frames the flood as a bounded covenant-event with a clear beginning and end. The household unit that enters and exits together is the covenant-unit that will receive the Noahic covenant in ch9 — the covenantal relationship is household-shaped from the outset.</p>""",
    "19": """<p>"All the animals... came out of the ark, one kind after another" — the orderly exit by kinds echoes the creation of each creature "according to its kind" (Gen 1:21,24,25). The ark's release of creatures by kind is the post-flood restoration of the creation taxonomy. The phrase "one kind after another" (<em>lĕmišpĕḥōtêhem</em>, by their families/clans) suggests an organized, not chaotic, exit — mirroring the orderly creation of Day 5-6 rather than suggesting a random dispersal. The post-flood world begins with the same order the pre-flood world had.</p>""",
    "20": """<p>Noah's first post-ark action is to build an altar (<em>mizbēaḥ</em>) and offer burnt offerings — the first altar in the biblical narrative. No divine command to sacrifice has been given; Noah acts on what covenantal instinct tells him is the appropriate response to preservation: gratitude expressed through sacrifice. The word <em>mizbēaḥ</em> (from <em>zāḇaḥ</em>, to slaughter/sacrifice) here marks the beginning of formal sacrificial worship before any Levitical law exists. The use of "some of all the clean animals and clean birds" explains retrospectively why seven pairs of clean animals were preserved (7:2-3): the surplus over the minimum breeding pair is needed for post-flood sacrifice without endangering species survival.</p>""",
    "21": """<p>"The LORD smelled the pleasing aroma (<em>rêaḥ hannîḥôaḥ</em>)" — the exact technical formula that will govern Levitical sacrifice throughout the Pentateuch (Lev 1:9,13,17; 2:2,9,12; 3:5; etc.). The post-flood sacrifice establishes the vocabulary and theology of acceptable sacrifice that the Mosaic system will codify. Crucially, the Gilgamesh epic contains a famous parallel: after Utnapishtim's sacrifice, "the gods crowded like flies over the sacrifice" because they had been deprived of food offerings during the flood. Genesis's version is emphatically different: YHWH's response is a unilateral covenant-resolution, not divine hunger appeased. The divine decision that follows — "never again will I curse the ground because of humans, even though every inclination of the human heart is evil from childhood" — repeats the pre-flood diagnosis of 6:5 verbatim. The flood did not solve the problem of human sin. The Noahic covenant is not conditional on human improvement; it is grace given to creatures who remain unchanged in their moral nature.</p>""",
    "22": """<p>"As long as the earth endures, seedtime and harvest, cold and heat, summer and winter, day and night will never cease" — the six paired terms constitute a covenant of cosmic preservation: the creation's seasonal rhythms are guaranteed as long as the earth exists. This is a proto-Noahic covenant that precedes the formal covenant of 9:8-17: YHWH commits to the maintenance of the created order on the basis of the acceptable sacrifice, not on the basis of human righteousness. The six pairs echo the six days of creation — the same creative order is now preserved by covenant promise. Paul's statement that creation was subjected to futility "in hope" (Rom 8:20) presupposes this covenant of cosmic maintenance: the creation groans but endures, because YHWH committed to it.</p>"""
  },
  "9": {
    "1": """<p>"God blessed Noah and his sons" — the creation blessing of 1:28 ("be fruitful and multiply and fill the earth") is restated word for word. The post-flood world is explicitly structured as a new creation: Noah is the new Adam, and the same creation mandate is given afresh. The same divine blessing that initiated human history at creation re-initiates it after the flood. The Noahic covenant that follows (vv8-17) is not merely a disaster-relief covenant but a re-creation covenant — the formal covenant establishment of a renewed humanity in a preserved world.</p>""",
    "2": """<p>"The fear and dread of you will fall on all the beasts of the earth" — the post-flood redefinition of the human-animal relationship. In ch1, the dominion mandate (1:28) describes human authority over animals without specifying the relational quality; the implicit harmony of the original creation is the assumed context. After the flood, the human-animal relationship is re-established in terms of dread — a significant darkening of the creation mandate. In ANE cosmological thinking, the removal of primordial harmony between humans and animals was a marker of the distance between the original created order and the current world. The post-flood world is not Eden restored; it is a post-Fall, post-flood world in which the covenants operate to preserve and govern fallen reality.</p>""",
    "3": """<p>"Everything that lives and moves about will be food for you. Just as I gave you the green plants, I now give you everything" — the original food grant of 1:29-30 gave only "green plants" (vegetation) to both humans and animals. The post-flood food grant explicitly expands human diet to include all living creatures. This is the first formal permission of meat-eating in the Bible — the Levitical dietary laws of Lev 11 will later specify which animals may and may not be eaten within this general permission. The phrase "just as I gave you the green plants" establishes a formal parallel between the creation food-gift and the post-flood food-gift — the latter is a covenant expansion, not a departure from the creation order.</p>""",
    "4": """<p>"But you must not eat meat that has its lifeblood still in it" — the blood-prohibition is the first explicit dietary law in the Bible, preceding the Mosaic system by centuries and therefore classified as a universal Noahic law. The theological basis is articulated in Lev 17:14: "the life of every creature is its blood." Blood equals life; to eat blood is to consume the life-principle that belongs to God alone — it is the prerogative of the Creator, not the creature. This pre-Mosaic, Noahic prohibition is cited in the Jerusalem Council (Acts 15:29) as one of the requirements for Gentile believers — confirming the early church's understanding that Noahic laws are universally binding, not restricted to Israel.</p>""",
    "5": """<p>"For your lifeblood I will surely demand an accounting" (<em>ʾak ʾet-dĕmêkem lĕnapšōtêkem ʾedrōš</em>) — the tripartite accountability formula (from every animal; from each human being; from each person's brother). The extension of moral accountability to animals who kill humans anticipates the goring-ox legislation of Exod 21:28-29, where a lethal ox must be stoned. The ancient world understood the entire creation as participating in the moral order — violence against the image-bearer created a moral debt not only for humans but for the creature who acted as the instrument of violence. Human blood, uniquely, demands divine accounting across every possible killer.</p>""",
    "6": """<p>"Whoever sheds human blood, by humans shall their blood be shed; for in the image of God (<em>bĕṣelem ʾĕlōhîm</em>) has God made mankind" — the lex talionis and its theological grounding are inseparable in this verse. The ground for capital punishment is not social utility or deterrence but the divine image: to kill a human being is to assault the image of the creator. This is one of only two places outside ch1 where the divine image is explicitly invoked in Genesis (cf. 5:1), confirming that the <em>ṣelem ʾĕlōhîm</em> survived the Fall and the flood. Rabbinic tradition identifies this verse as the scriptural basis for the Noahide commandment prohibiting murder — one of the seven laws binding on all humanity (<em>Tosefta Avodah Zarah</em> 8:4). The image-of-God grounding of human dignity is not a later theological development but is written into the first universal covenant.</p>""",
    "7": """<p>The double fruitfulness mandate (here and v1) brackets the Noahic legislation of vv2-6. The re-statement at the covenant's close confirms that the covenant's ethical requirements (vv2-6) are not burdens imposed on human existence but the conditions under which the creation mandate can be fulfilled. Human dignity (v6: image of God), human protection (v5: blood-accounting), and human food-provision (vv3-4) are the prerequisites for the fruitfulness and multiplication that God intends for the new humanity. The Noahic covenant is a covenant that makes human flourishing possible.</p>""",
    "8": """<p>"Then God said to Noah and to his sons with him" — the formal covenant-declaration opening addresses both Noah and his sons explicitly. The covenant is explicitly intergenerational from its first statement: "you and your sons with him." The sons are not covenant-beneficiaries by derivation from Noah but are themselves directly addressed as covenant-parties. The household-covenant pattern established in Gen 6:18 (Noah's family included in the ark-covenant) is confirmed and formalized here.</p>""",
    "9": """<p>"I now establish my covenant with you and with your descendants after you" — the Noahic covenant is the first fully formal covenant in the Bible (the word <em>bĕrît</em> was introduced in 6:18 as a commitment to be "established," now it is "established"). The verb <em>hăqîmōtî</em> (I establish/confirm) — hiphil of <em>qûm</em> — is consistently used for the formal ratification of covenants already implicitly in place: the same verb is used for the Abrahamic covenant (17:7,19,21), the covenant with Isaac (17:21), and the Mosaic covenant (Exod 6:4). The "establishing" language suggests the Noahic covenant is not invented from nothing but formalizes the creation-order preservation that YHWH committed to in 8:21-22.</p>""",
    "10": """<p>"Every living creature that was with you — the birds, the livestock and all the wild animals, all those that came out of the ark" — the Noahic covenant's unprecedented scope. Unlike every other biblical covenant, which is particularist (with Abraham's family, with Israel, with David's house), the Noahic covenant is explicitly universal: it includes "every living creature on earth," not only the human parties. The covenant encompasses the entire biosphere — birds, livestock, wild animals — as covenant parties. This ecological dimension of the Noahic covenant is the foundational basis for a biblical theology of creation-care: the non-human creation is in covenant relationship with YHWH, not merely the background against which human covenant operates.</p>""",
    "11": """<p>"Never again will all life be destroyed by the waters of a flood; never again will there be a flood to destroy the earth" — the double negative (<em>lōʾ-yiqqārēt kol-bāśār ʿôd</em>; <em>lōʾ-yihyeh ʿôd mabbûl</em>) is the most emphatic possible covenant-commitment in Hebrew. The word "cut off" (<em>kārat</em>) is the standard covenant-violation term — the same word used in the covenant-making formula (<em>kārat bĕrît</em>, to "cut" a covenant) and in the judgment of those who violate it (to be "cut off" from the community). The flood had "cut off" all flesh; the covenant now commits to never repeating that cutting-off. The earth will eventually end (Isa 51:6; 2 Pet 3:10), but not by flood — the Noahic covenant is specific and limited, not a guarantee of eternal terrestrial permanence.</p>""",
    "12": """<p>"This is the sign (<em>ʾôt</em>) of the covenant I am making between me and you and every living creature" — the covenant-sign is introduced in the same language as other covenantal signs (<em>ʾôt</em>): circumcision (17:11), the Sabbath (Exod 31:13), and Passover blood (Exod 12:13). Every major biblical covenant has a sign; the Noahic covenant's sign is the rainbow. The phrase "for all generations to come" (<em>lĕḏōrōt ʿôlām</em>) extends the covenant's sign beyond the immediate flood-survivors to all subsequent humanity — the rainbow is a permanent covenantal institution, not a temporary memorial.</p>""",
    "13": """<p>"I have set my rainbow in the clouds, and it will be the sign of the covenant between me and the earth" — the Hebrew <em>qešet</em> (rainbow) is the same word for a warrior's bow or battle-bow (Gen 27:3; 48:22; Josh 24:12). The choice of the bow as the covenant-sign carries a possible ANE resonance: in Babylonian mythology, Marduk hangs his bow in the heavens after defeating Tiamat in the Enuma Elish — the warrior-god's weapon stored as a sign that the battle is over. Whether or not this background is intentionally invoked, the Hebrew <em>qešet</em> carries both the rainbow and the warrior-bow meaning. YHWH's bow set in the clouds can be read as the divine warrior's weapon hung at rest — the one who executed judgment through the flood now lays down his weapon as a sign of peace.</p>""",
    "14": """<p>"Whenever I bring clouds over the earth and the rainbow appears in the clouds" — the covenant's sign is weather-contingent but not weather-dependent. Every storm that produces clouds has the potential to produce the sign; YHWH's commitment is renewed at each appearance. In the ANE, storms were understood as theophanic events — the storm is where the divine warrior acts (cf. Ps 29; Job 38-39; Exod 19). Every storm that comes with clouds is now simultaneously a potential occasion for the divine warrior's sign of restraint. The clouds that could signal more judgment produce instead the sign of preserved covenant.</p>""",
    "15": """<p>"I will remember my covenant between me and you and all living creatures of every kind" — for the second time (cf. 8:1, where God remembered Noah), the divine-remembering vocabulary anchors the covenant's preservation in YHWH's own active faithfulness. The covenant sign is not primarily for humans to see and be reassured but for God to see and act — "I will see it and remember" (v16). This inversion of normal covenant-sign usage (where signs are typically for the human parties) is theologically distinctive: the covenant is held by YHWH's own perception of his own sign. The eternal security of the covenant rests in divine memory, not human fidelity.</p>""",
    "16": """<p>"The everlasting covenant (<em>bĕrît ʿôlām</em>) between God and all living creatures of every kind on the earth" — the Noahic covenant is the first explicitly everlasting (<em>ʿôlām</em>) covenant in the Bible. The same phrase characterizes the Abrahamic covenant (17:7,13,19), the Priestly/Phinehas covenant (Num 25:13), the Davidic covenant (2 Sam 23:5; Isa 55:3), the new covenant (Jer 32:40; Isa 61:8; Ezek 37:26), and the covenant of peace (Isa 54:10). The Noahic <em>bĕrît ʿôlām</em> is the foundational link in this chain of everlasting covenants that structure the entire canon. Each subsequent everlasting covenant narrows the scope of covenant-participants (Noahic: all flesh; Abrahamic: one family; Mosaic: one nation; Davidic: one king; New: the new covenant community) while deepening the covenantal relationship.</p>""",
    "17": """<p>"This is the sign of the covenant I have established (<em>hăqîmōtî</em>) between me and all life on the earth" — the formal closing formula of the covenant restates the establishment verb (<em>qûm</em> hiphil) that opened the covenant unit in v9. The bracketing of the covenant (vv9 and 17) with the same "establish" verb is the Hebrew prose convention for marking a complete literary unit — the Noahic covenant is a structurally bounded, complete textual unit. The final statement is addressed to Noah directly, not to the animals or all creatures — confirming that Noah (and through him, his sons) is the human covenant mediator for the universal covenant.</p>""",
    "18": """<p>"Ham was the father of Canaan" — this parenthetical note is a narrative telegraph: the reader is being prepared before the episode of vv20-27 to understand why the curse in v25 falls on Canaan rather than on Ham directly. The mention of Canaan before the episode creates an anticipatory frame — the reader who encounters "cursed be Canaan" in v25 has already been primed to understand Canaan as the relevant descendant of Ham. The note also begins the Table of Nations trajectory: Shem, Ham, Japheth will unfold into all the peoples of the earth in ch10.</p>""",
    "19": """<p>"From them came the people who were scattered over the whole earth" — the word "scattered" (<em>nāpĕṣāh</em>) is the same verb used for the scattering at Babel (11:4,8,9: YHWH "scattered them over the face of the whole earth"). The prospective note connecting the flood survivors to the Table of Nations (ch10) and the Babel scattering (ch11) weaves these chapters into a unified post-flood narrative. The three sons are not merely genealogical starting points but the theological foundations for understanding how one covenant-household became all humanity.</p>""",
    "20": """<p>"Noah, a man of the soil (<em>ʾîš hāʾădāmāh</em>), proceeded to plant a vineyard" — the phrase <em>ʾîš hāʾădāmāh</em> (man of the soil/ground) echoes Gen 2:7 (<em>ʾādām</em> formed from the <em>ʾădāmāh</em>, ground) and 3:23 (Adam sent to work the ground from which he was taken). Noah the post-flood new Adam resumes the agricultural vocation of the first Adam. The planting of a vineyard represents the development of agriculture beyond subsistence farming — viticulture requires long-term investment (vines take years to produce) and the cultural infrastructure of wine-making. Wine-culture appears here for the first time in the Bible; its first recorded use produces the narrative crisis of vv21-25.</p>""",
    "21": """<p>Noah "became drunk and lay uncovered (<em>wayyitgal</em>) inside his tent" — <em>ʿerwāh</em> (nakedness, uncovering) carries profound cultural weight in the ancient world. Adam and Eve's nakedness-awareness after the Fall (3:7) was the first marker of shame and fallen social order; YHWH covered them with garments of skin (3:21). In the Levitical code, "uncovering nakedness" (<em>gālāh ʿerwāh</em>) is consistently the euphemism for sexual violation (Lev 18:6-19; 20:11-21). Noah's uncovered state inside his tent is his fallen-Adam vulnerability: the one who survived the flood and received the covenant is not thereby exempt from the human-sin pattern established in chs 3-4.</p>""",
    "22": """<p>"Ham, the father of Canaan, saw his father naked and told his two brothers outside" — the exact nature of Ham's offense is one of the most debated textual questions in Genesis. At minimum, the offense involves making visible what should remain concealed — a profound violation of patriarchal honor in ANE culture. To see and then publicize a patriarch's shameful vulnerability is the inverse of Shem and Japheth's covering act (v23). Some interpreters argue for a more serious offense — sexual violation or castration — based on the severity of the curse, the euphemistic language ("what his youngest son had done to him," v24), and the Levitical coding of "uncovering nakedness" as sexual violation. The narrative does not explicitly state what occurred beyond "saw his father naked"; the ambiguity is in the text and should not be resolved by interpretive overclaiming in either direction.</p>""",
    "23": """<p>Shem and Japheth's act of covering their father — walking in backward, faces averted, laying the garment over Noah — is a counter-act of honor in the ANE honor-shame framework. Where Ham exposed, they concealed; where Ham publicized, they acted privately; where Ham showed disrespect to a superior, they showed honor. The backward walking to avoid seeing their father's nakedness is an extraordinary act of deliberate unseeing — the active refusal to know what Ham made known. The covering with a garment echoes YHWH's garment-making for Adam and Eve (3:21): the gesture of covering shame is a theologically resonant act of covenant-fidelity throughout the canon.</p>""",
    "24": """<p>"When Noah awoke from his wine and found out what his youngest son had done to him" — the identification of Ham as "youngest son" (<em>bĕnô haqqāṭān</em>) is textually puzzling, since the genealogies consistently list Japheth as the youngest (born after Shem and Ham). Some interpreters propose that <em>haqqāṭān</em> here refers to Canaan (Ham's son) as the actual agent of the offense, explaining why the curse falls on Canaan rather than Ham. Others understand the genealogical lists as not uniformly representing birth order. The ambiguity may be intentional: the narrative focuses on the moral offense and the covenant-consequences, not on the genealogical technicality.</p>""",
    "25": """<p>"Cursed be Canaan! The lowest of slaves will he be to his brothers" — the curse falls on Canaan specifically, not on Ham or all of Ham's descendants. In the Table of Nations (ch10), Canaan is the ancestor of the Canaanites — the inhabitants of the promised land whom Israel will later subjugate (cf. Josh 9:23; Judg 1:28). The curse is the theological explanation within the Genesis narrative for the later Israelite-Canaanite relationship, not a universal statement about any ethnic group. It is impossible to overstate the importance of noting the catastrophic misuse of this text in Western history as a justification for African slavery: that reading is exegetically indefensible on multiple grounds. (1) In ch10, the African peoples (Cush, Mizraim, Put) are descendants of Ham's <em>other</em> sons, not of Canaan. (2) The curse is on one specific genealogical line of one son of Ham. (3) The text's own application is to the Canaanites, explicitly. The "curse of Ham" as a racial category has no basis in the text.</p>""",
    "26": """<p>"Blessed be the LORD, the God of Shem! May Canaan be the slave of Shem" — Shem's blessing is framed theologically rather than materially: the content of the blessing is that YHWH is "the God of Shem." This is the first time in the Bible that the covenant-formula "God of [person]" is used — the formula that will become the definitive covenant-relationship expression ("the God of Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob," Exod 3:6; "the God of Shem" establishes the Semitic covenant trajectory. The Abrahamic covenant (Gen 12; 15; 17) flows from this Shem-blessing as the formal covenant with one family within the broader Semitic covenant-line.</p>""",
    "27": """<p>"May God extend Japheth's territory; may Japheth live in the tents of Shem" — the blessing on Japheth is territorial (expansion) rather than theologically relational. The phrase "live in the tents of Shem" has been interpreted by many interpreters as Japheth sharing in the spiritual blessings of the Semitic covenant-community — an early anticipation of Gentile inclusion in the covenant. Paul's language of Gentiles (Japhethic peoples) being "grafted into" the olive tree of Israel (Rom 11:17-19) and the breaking down of the dividing wall between Jew and Gentile (Eph 2:14) may be read as the fulfillment of this Japheth-in-Shem's-tents blessing. The three-tier covenant structure (Shem: covenantal relationship; Japheth: territorial expansion with access to Shem's blessing; Canaan: subjugation) is the charter for the post-flood family-of-nations covenant pattern.</p>""",
    "28": """<p>Noah lives 350 years after the flood — the post-flood lifespan, significantly shorter than the pre-flood antediluvian figures (Noah's pre-flood lifespan was already 600 years when the flood came). The pattern of dramatically shortened lifespans after the flood is a consistent feature of the Genesis genealogies (cf. ch11's post-flood genealogy: Shem 600 years, Arphaxad 438, Shelah 433, Eber 464, Peleg 239, Reu 239, Serug 230, Nahor 148, Terah 205). The Sumerian King List similarly records dramatically shortened lifespans for post-flood kings compared to the antediluvian kings (pre-flood kings: 28,800–36,000 years; post-flood kings: 1,200–1,500 years). Whether the reduction reflects a literal biological change, a different counting system, or a symbolic compression, the pattern of decreasing lifespans from creation to the patriarchs is consistent across both traditions.</p>""",
    "29": """<p>"Noah lived a total of 950 years, and then he died" — the death-refrain that structured ch5's genealogy returns for the last time. Noah's death at 950 years closes the flood narrative's biographical frame and ends the antediluvian/immediate post-flood era. The refrain "and then he died" — sounded eleven times in ch5 (with the single exception of Enoch) and now once more for Noah — is the genealogy's acknowledgment that even the covenant-mediator, even the one who survived the flood and received the Noahic covenant, is mortal. The flood did not restore the pre-Fall immortality of Eden. Only the eschatological new creation will definitively end the death-refrain (Rev 21:4: "there will be no more death").</p>"""
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-context', 'genesis')
    before_count = sum(len(v) for v in existing.values())
    merge_comm(existing, GENESIS_CONTEXT)
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'genesis', existing)

    result = load_comm('mkt-context', 'genesis')
    after_count = sum(len(v) for v in result.values())
    print(f'  Verses added: {after_count - before_count}')
    for ch in [7, 8, 9]:
        ck = str(ch)
        n = len(result.get(ck, {}))
        print(f'  Ch {ch}: {n} verses present')
    total_chs = len(result)
    total_vv = sum(len(v) for v in result.values())
    print(f'  Genesis context total: {total_chs} chapters, {total_vv} verses')
    print('Genesis 7–9 mkt-context written.')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
